    "country": "USA",
    "bio": "Jane Doe is Professor of Public Policy at George Washington University, where she directs the Center for Urban Mobility Research. Her work sits at the intersection of transportation engineering, behavioral economics, and public policy, with a particular focus on how pricing schemes and information nudges shape commuter choice in mid-sized US cities.\n\nBefore joining GWU in 2014, she spent five years at the US Department of Transportation Office of Policy Analysis and held a postdoctoral fellowship at MIT's Center for Transportation and Logistics. She has published in the American Economic Review, the Journal of Public Economics, and Transportation Research Part A, and her congestion-pricing pilots in Denver and Pittsburgh have informed legislation in both cities.\n\nShe currently serves on the National Academies' standing committee on Travel Behavior and Values and is a frequent commentator for outlets including The Atlantic and NPR's Marketplace.",
